	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Apr 4th 7:03 AM 2002</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.58]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I'm assuming you are planning on making money from providing XP rezzes.&nbsp;&nbsp;If that is the case, you may want to rethink your strategy.  Here's why:<br><br>1) Spell Components get pricey.  You should be symboling the MA and casting it on yourself so you know when tho recast on the MA.  Symbols require gems which get more expensive with each newer and better Symbols.  Conscientious players carry these gems with them to give to the cleric if they want Symbols cast on them...but MOST players do not do this.<br><br>2) Spells get steadily more and more expensive as you level.  As a caster class, your spells define you.  This means that you need to have the latest and greatest spells for your level, otherwise your job is MUCH harder.  This means that you must save plat all the time for your next spell ring...because you may be dead broke after buying those spells.  It takes a LOT of time, effort and cash to get to the magic &quot;UBER&quot; loot where money is no object, and everyone and their mothers, friends, pets, and even complete strangers get symbols &quot;just because&quot;.<br><br>3) A good cleric keeps the manna regenerating by keeping his butt parked on the pavement.  This means you might not get to loot when it is your turn (if in an alpha loot situation, or even a FFA situation).  You do this to keep people alive, and good players will recognize that, and share the wealth.  But don't expect this all the time, not everyone learns how the other people in the group work. <br><br>4)Fringe benefits come to those who rez for free or voluntary donations.  Get a rep as a greedy moneygrubber and not too many people will send you tells for your services.  As an example, I was hunting in KC one day on my Ranger.  There was a group camping Venril Sathir, a bad Epic mob for Druids and Rangers (and also some nice rare drops).  This group could not control VS and did not know how to get out without training VS to the zone.  This resulted in multiple deaths for everyone in the zone.  The cleric in the VS group actually took cash from people whose deaths he and his group were responsible for.  No one got a free rez from him.  He made a nice chunk of change for his 90% rezzes, but his reputation took a nose dive.  (as an aside, people were so sick of the VS trains that another guild sent about 20 55+ peeps on short notice and killed VS at the zone line with the next train...)<br><br>5) WIS gear can be a pain to get ahold of.  It's not as easy to get WIS gear as it is for INT gear, so WIS gear is generally pricier on the open market.  You will need WIS gear upgrades as you level and your spells require more and more manna per cast.<br><br>6) By the time you get to the point where the cash from vouluntary donations for XP rezzes can be a nice chunk of change, your gear will have evened out any racial plusses or minuses you started with.  Gnome clerics are just as good as High Elf clerics in the end game due to eguipment.  You cant get above the 255 cap in the end, and the 1 point of manna per WIS point above 200 means getting to the cap may not be all that great. <br><br>So, hope that helps you a little.  Don't know where monk stuff drops, never played a monk, so I've never paid attention.  Can't tell you what armor or jewelry to get without knowing your server or budget.  The only thing I can tell you is to go for WIS first, AC next, and the rest is gravy...+manna items are nice, but +WIS is better in the long run.<br>&nbsp;<br>Colphax<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=187084" target=_new>http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=187084</a><br>Baradur 30 Human Cleric<br>Malden 16 Dwarven Warrior</td></tr>
